                <head>170. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>Sections of <gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> 5407 (which replaced <gloss
                        target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> 161), “Status of United States Programs for
                    National Security as of December 31, 1953,” were circulated on February 17,
                    1954, and in subsequent circulars as they were prepared. The report was
                    discussed at the 187th, 188th, and 190th meetings of the <gloss target="#t_NSC1"
                        >NSC</gloss> on March 4, 11, and 25, 1954. (National Archives, RG 59,
                        S/S–<gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> Files: Lot 63 D 351, <gloss
                        target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> 5407) Part 8, “The Foreign Intelligence
                    Program” was prepared by the Central Intelligence Agency. (<persName
                        corresp="#p_EDD1">Eisenhower</persName> Library, White House Office, Office
                    of the Special Assistant for National Security Affairs, <gloss target="#t_NSC1"
                        >NSC</gloss> Series, Status of Projects, <gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss>
                    5407, Boxes 4–5) <gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> 5407 is discussed in an
                    editorial note in <ref target="frus1952-54v02p1#pg_633">
                        <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1952–1954, volume II, Part 1, page
                        633</ref>.</p>
            </div>
